Group Project / Honey Drip Group Members : Egemen Onat Atam, Uğur Özata, Bayram Saygılı, Yaser Girit, Bengü Üzmez Introduction Anime has a large and dedicated following all over the world, and understanding the preferences and behaviors of anime fans can be valuable for industry professionals and researchers alike. In this project, we will be working with five datasets related to anime that are available on Kaggle. The datasets contain information on anime titles, genres, ratings, synopsis, and user behavior. By applying statistical and data mining techniques, we aim to extract insights and identify trends and patterns within the anime community.

The specific objectives of this project are to:

Explore the characteristics of popular anime titles Identify factors that contribute to high ratings for anime Analyze the preferences of anime fans based on their ratings and watching habits Understand the dynamics of the anime community by analyzing user behavior data We will begin by providing a detailed description of the datasets and the data cleaning and preprocessing steps that were taken. The main analysis and findings will be presented in the subsequent sections, followed by a conclusion and recommendations for further study. Through this project, we hope to gain a better understanding of the anime community and provide valuable insights for professionals and researchers.

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing: Before we can begin our analysis, it is important to ensure that the data is clean and ready for processing. The first step in this process is to split the "Aired" column into "start_date" and "end_date" columns, and convert them to datetime format. We will also drop the original "Aired" column.

Next, we will replace the "Unknown" values with null. We will also convert the "Score", "Ranked", "Rating", and "Members" columns to integers, as well as the "Score-1" to "Score-10" columns.

Once the data has been cleaned and preprocessed, we can begin the analysis. We will start by exploring the characteristics of popular anime titles, including their genres, ratings, and other factors that may contribute to their popularity. We will also analyze the preferences of anime fans based on their ratings and watching habits, and understand the dynamics of the anime community by analyzing user behavior data.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
anime = pd.read_csv("C:/Users/USER/Desktop/anime.csv")
# Split the "aired" column into two columns using the "to" delimiter
anime[["start_date", "end_date"]] = anime["Aired"].str.split(" to ", expand=True)
anime["start_date"] = pd.to_datetime(anime["start_date"], errors="coerce")
anime["end_date"] = pd.to_datetime(anime["end_date"], errors="coerce")
# Drop the original "aired" column
anime = anime.drop("Aired", axis=1)
# Replace the "Unknown" values with NaN
anime = anime.replace('Unknown', float('nan'))

# Convert the Score, Ranked, Rating, and Members columns to integers
anime['Score'] = pd.to_numeric(anime['Score'], downcast='integer')
anime['Ranked'] = pd.to_numeric(anime['Ranked'], downcast='integer')
anime['Members'] = pd.to_numeric(anime['Members'], downcast='integer')
anime['Episodes'] = pd.to_numeric(anime['Episodes'], downcast='integer')
# Convert the Score-1 to Score-10 columns to integers
for i in range(1, 11):
    column_name = f'Score-{i}'
    anime[column_name] = pd.to_numeric(anime[column_name], downcast='integer')
anime.head(1)

The both score plots shows the distribution of scores for all anime titles in the dataset. From the plot, we can see that the majority of anime titles have scores between 5 and 8, with a smaller number of titles having scores below 5 or above 8. This suggests that the majority of anime titles are considered to be of average quality, with relatively fewer titles that are highly rated or poorly rated.

There are several possible explanations for this pattern. One possibility is that the average quality of anime titles has remained relatively consistent over time, with only a small proportion being exceptional or subpar. Another possibility is that there may be biases in the ratings, such as a tendency for users to give higher scores to certain genres or studios, or a tendency to rate more recent titles higher due to nostalgia or hype.

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
# Create a scatter plot with the Type column as the hue
sns.scatterplot(x="Score", y="Popularity", hue="Type", data=anime)
plt.title("Score-Popularity/Type")
# Show the plot
plt.show()

The scatter plot shows the relationship between the score and popularity of anime titles, colored by type. From the plot, we can see that there is a general trend of lower scores corresponding to higher popularity. This suggests that anime titles with lower scores tend to be more popular among users, while those with higher scores are less popular.

One possible explanation for this pattern is that users may be more attracted to anime titles with more mainstream or commercial appeal, which may not necessarily be highly rated by critics or more discerning viewers. This could also be due to a preference for certain types of anime, such as music or slice-of-life, which tend to have lower scores but higher popularity.

It is also worth noting that there are a few exceptions to this trend, such as some music and sports anime titles that have relatively high scores but lower popularity. This could be due to a variety of factors, such as the niche appeal of these genres or the influence of other variables such as production values or storytelling.

Overall, this plot highlights the complexity of the relationship between score and popularity in the anime industry, and suggests that there may be multiple factors at play.

SELECT COALESCE(producers, 'Unknown') AS producer, AVG(score) AS avg_score
FROM anime
GROUP BY producer
HAVING COUNT(*) >= 15
ORDER BY avg_score DESC
LIMIT 15;

%%sql
SELECT AVG(Score) as mean_score, Genres
FROM anime
GROUP BY Genres
HAVING Genres IN (SELECT Genres FROM (
    SELECT Genres, COUNT(*) as count
    FROM anime
    GROUP BY Genres
    ORDER BY count DESC
    LIMIT 10
) top_genres)

%%sql
SELECT a.name, a.score, a.genres, a.type, aws.sypnopsis, al.rating, al.watching_status
FROM anime a
JOIN anime_with_synopsis aws ON a.mal_id = aws.mal_id
JOIN animelist al ON a.mal_id = al.anime_id
WHERE a.score > 9
LIMIT 10;

In this EDA, we analyzed several datasets related to anime, including the 'anime' dataset, 'anime_with_synopsis' dataset, 'animelist' dataset, 'rating_complete' dataset, and 'watching_status' dataset. We used various statistical and data mining techniques to extract insights from the data, including cleaning and preprocessing the data and applying appropriate algorithms to find patterns and trends.

Through our analysis, we discovered several interesting trends and patterns within the anime community. For example, we found that the most popular genres of anime are Hentai, Music, and Comedy, and that most anime titles have a score between 5 and 8. We also found that the number of anime titles has increased over the past 20 years, with a significant increase in the quality of anime productions in recent years.

We also found that the top 3 producers by the number of anime titles are NHK, Pink Pineapple, and Sanrio, while the top 3 producers by average score are VAP, Nippon Television Network, and Shochiku. This suggests that while these top 3 producers have produced fewer anime titles overall, the quality of their productions is higher, as measured by the average score.

In addition, we explored the relationship between the number of episodes and the score of anime titles and found that there is a general trend of lower scores corresponding to higher episode count. This could be due to a variety of factors, such as the difficulty of maintaining a high level of quality over a long period of time, or the challenge of keeping the audience engaged for an extended period. There are some exceptions to this trend, such as some long-running series that have relatively high scores despite their large episode count. These could be examples of exceptional or highly popular series that have managed to maintain a high level of quality and engagement over a longer period.

Overall, this EDA has provided valuable insights into the anime community and has identified several areas for further study. Some potential next steps could include analyzing user ratings and preferences to better understand the factors that contribute to the popularity and success of anime titles. These insights can be used to inform the production and distribution of anime, as well as to help users discover new and highly rated titles.
